         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (who) endures (reproach)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (and for reasons of) impetuosity, (to a fellow man)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] the wise call that (the highest form of) endurance</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] in assemblies (or) privately [SKT] (when man is overcome) by anger</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] one should speak what is true, one should not be angry</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] provided with these three (things) [TB] (provided with these three) things</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] from where could anger come (to the tranquil man) [SKT] who is restrained (and lives in balance?)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] for him who understands, there is no (anger) [TB] (for him who understands, there is no) anger</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] he who, being angered, becomes angry in return [SKT] (but who is not angered) with [others’] angers</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] he would win (a fight that is difficult to win) [TB] (he would win) a fight that is difficult to win</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB] (one should overcome) evil with the good</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT] (from where could anger come) to him who is not angry</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">The fragment is archaic because it shows <hi>ä</hi> for class. <hi>a</hi> (/ə́/) and <hi>ew</hi> for class. <hi>au</hi>: <hi>ñäṣträ</hi> a2; <hi>wäntärwa(sa)</hi> a7 <hi>kärttsewñe(sa)</hi> b5.</note><note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>273-276</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:chakravarti1930"/><citedRange>255-257</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>71-72</citedRange></bibl></note><note type="remarks">The fragments IOL Toch 809 and IOL Toch 1244 belong to the same leaf: IOL Toch 1244 a5 (the last line) is continued by IOL Toch 809 a5 (the first line), and IOL Toch 809 b3 (the last line) continues IOL Toch 1244 b3 (the first line). Since the precise wording of the Tocharian text in both instances is not known, it is not feasible to reconstruct an image or to count out the number of missing syllables, if any.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.20.13d <hi>yo ’tivākyaṃ titīkṣati</hi></note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Uv.20.14b <hi>saṃrambhahetoḥ sadṛśasya caiva</hi></note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Uv.20.14d <hi>tām uttamāṃ kṣāntim ihāhur āryāḥ</hi>. We find <hi>ārya</hi> for regular <hi>āryāḥ</hi>, but note that the pausa visarga is not written in this manuscript: it lacks in a5 for <hi>mithaḥ</hi> (<hi>– •</hi> instead), in a7 for <hi>yuktaḥ</hi> (<hi>yukta •</hi> instead) and in b3 for <hi>punaḥ</hi> (<hi>n· •</hi> instead).</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Uv.20.15b-c <hi>pariṣatsv atha vā mithaḥ / krodhābhibhūtaḥ puruṣaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">The reading of this line is particularly uncertain (and changed slightly compared to <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2008a"/><citedRange>103</citedRange></bibl>), since in IOL Toch 1244 only the upper part of some akṣaras is visible, and in IOL Toch 809 only the lower. As I do not know how to restore the whole line, the number of missing syllables is uncertain; it is possible that the last <hi>e</hi>-vowel of IOL Toch 1244 belongs to (the first akṣara of) <hi>ṣemeske</hi> on IOL Toch 809.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment">Uv.20.16a <hi>satyaṃ vaden na ca krudhyed</hi></note><note corresp="#a7" type="philcomment">Uv.20.16c <hi>sthānair ebhis tribhir yukto</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.20.17a-b <hi>śāntasya hi kutaḥ krodho dāntasya samajīvinaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.20.17d <hi>krodho nāsti prajānataḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">traces of the <hi>c</hi> and the <hi>o</hi> of <hi>ścono</hi> can be seen, too.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.20.18b-c <hi>yaḥ kruddhe krudhyate punaḥ | kruddheṣv akruddhamānas tu</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">On IOL Toch 809, a little piece from the recto is flipped over at the left. I do not know how to restore this line either, so the number of missing akṣaras, if any, is uncertain. In <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2008a"/><citedRange>104</citedRange></bibl> I had reconstructed a loc.sg. <hi>(ś)c(o)n(aine)</hi>, which is not in accordance with the manuscript traces: what seems to be <hi>[c]</hi> (the line is going slightly up) suggests rather an all.sg. <hi>(ś)c(o)n(aiś)c(ä)</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Uv.20.18d <hi>saṃgrāmaṃ durjayaṃ jayet</hi></note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">Uv.20.19b <hi>asādhuṃ sādhunā jayet</hi></note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment">Uv.20.20a <hi>akruddhasya kutaḥ krodho</hi>, here apparently <hi>akrudha(sya)</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
